issue.title: [MVP P1] My Hand: fan layout with overlap and responsive scaling
issue.body:
Make the My Hand display feel like real cards.

Acceptance criteria:
- Cards rendered in a slight arc/fan with small overlap and z-order
- Scales down gracefully on narrow screens; wraps or shrinks width
- No layout jank on orientation or window resize
- Works in mock mode; no new dependencies unless necessary

Definition of done:
- Code, tests (golden or widget), and a short GIF in README/screenshots

comment.body:
Implemented the fan/arc layout for â€œMy Handâ€ with overlap, slight rotation, and responsive scaling. Wired into TableScreen and added a basic widget test.

Highlights:
- New `FanHand` widget (`lib/ui/widgets/fan_hand.dart`) lays cards in an arc with adjustable overlap and max angle; auto-scales to fit width.
- Table UI now uses `FanHand.builder` to render the hand while preserving legal/turn gating and existing slide animation.
- Added `test/fan_hand_test.dart` to confirm scaling and item building; full test suite green.
- README updated to mention the fan layout.

If you want a steeper arc or tighter overlap, I can tweak `maxAngleDeg`/`overlapFraction` defaults or expose a setting.

issue.body:
### systemd version the issue has been seen with

257.6

### Used distribution

Nixos

### Linux kernel version used

6.16

### CPU architectures issue was seen on

x86_64

### Component

systemd-nspawn


### Unexpected behaviour you saw

When mounting a single file inside a symlink directory with idmap and privateUsers=pick, the container fail to start.

### Steps to reproduce the problem


mkdir /a/
touch /a/file
ln -s /a/ /b/
try to start the container with --bind(-ro or not)=/b/file:/b/file:idmap

### Additional program output to the terminal or log subsystem illustrating the issue

```sh
systemd-nspawn[54399]: Failed to map ids for bind mount /run/nixos-containers/.#machinename4719ff62fce7ecfc/a/single/file: Invalid argument
```

comment.body: After some search, this seems to be reasonable behavior, as bind mount should not follow symlink to prevent container escape. I'm was surprised by the error message before even getting that the file I want to mount is symlinked but I've found a workaround on my case (CF:https://github.com/Mic92/sops-nix/issues/719)
